<font color="#FF0000">PERSONAL ACCOUNTABILITY</font><br>
<tt>Sat May 17 13:18:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Two things, not really related.<br>
(1) Thanks Arthur.  <br>
(2) The following seemed to jump out my my skull this morning, and it prompted two letters to the editor, one at the NY Times, (sort of shoot for the top) and the other for the local paper here, the Orange County Register.  I thought I'd share it, as we all seem to not trust &quot;our&quot; government, but just who is the government? It could be the guy next door or the woman across the street.  As long as individuals can hide behind the phrase of &quot;the government&quot; they will never have to be responsible, or accountable, and they get to remain REMF's, no?<br><br>
Editor: Re: Tuskeegee Survivors<br><br>
President Clinton offered long over due apoligies to the survivors and families of a science project gone astray, for 40 years, in the name of &quot;the government&quot;.<br><br>
The apology is right. The use of &quot;the government&quot; is wrong.<br><br>
Who, exactly, name and bio, please, Mr. President,authorized this &quot;research&quot;?  Exactly how many doctors and staff, THEIR NAMES PLEASE, were involved?<br><br>
Until we as a people stop hiding behind the facade of &quot;the government&quot; and start dealing with individuals, not agencies, but people, singular or plural, we will never have to take responsibility or accountability for &quot;the government&quot; and its actions.  I am &quot;the government, you are the government, we all are the government&quot; and that broad-brush stroke has gone on for too long.<br><br>
I want individual accountability. I want names, not empty titles or department labels.  Who was responsible and why are no charges being considered?   It's time for all of us to stop &quot;the government&quot; from being used by individuals to hide behind and within.<br><br>
Dr. Barry Spatz<br>
Orange County, CA<br><br>
Your thoughts gang?
